post_text:
Midland Academy Parents & Students,

Please allow us to commend you all on your quick response to our early dismissal on Thursday. Your ability to respond without delay or hesitation ensured the safety of all students and staff. It also allowed Oncor the opportunity to react to our power outage quickly and get MACS up and running again.

This unique situation also gave us a chance to explore what MACS @ home learning would look like for the entire campus. Please give yourself a pat on the back for helping that be successful with little to no problems. Your ability to adjust to the situation furthered our confidence in you, and for that, we thank you.

That being said, school will resume on Monday, August 24th. We are eager to get back to the new normal and see all our student‚Äôs smiling faces whether in person or virtual. Enjoy the rest of your weekend and we will see you Monday morning.

MACS Staff

post_text:
ATTENTION PARENTS!!!

MACS is currently experiencing a power outage. Oncor is working on the situation. Unfortunately, it may take a few days to fix. Due to this, we are needing all students to be picked up IMMEDIATELY Please follow the usual dismissal procedures and know that it may take a bit due to only half of our school having electricity. Use the drive thru or playground only.

School will be conducted virtually at home starting tomorrow, August 20th. Your child's teacher will be in contact with you asap.

Please be on the look out for updated information on Sunday evening.

Thank you for your understanding.

Leneise Reid
Superintendent

National School Choice Week shines a spotlight on effective education options for every child. To honor National School Choice Week, Midland City Council District 4 Person, Lori Blong, read a proclamation declaring this week as National School Choice Week. In appreciation of the proclamation, Mrs. Taylor presented Mrs. Blong with an art piece and MACS jaguar presented her with a National School Choice scarf. Art piece was created by Mrs. Taylor.

Pictured from left to right: Lori Blong, Midland Academy Jaguar, and Middle School Teacher Mrs. Taylor.

post_text: Our MACS middle school students were visited by the Midland Rockhounds & Rocky the Rockhound today. Rocky & the Rockhounds encourage students to stay drug free and remain in school through their Scoring in Schools program. The program stresses saying "NO" to drugs, staying in school, working as a team, & being physically fit. Thank you to Rocky and the Midland Rockhounds for stressing such important messages.

post_text: We had our Kids Heart Challenge ( formerly Jump Rope for Heart ‚ô•Ô∏è) Kickoff on Friday. We will jump rope in P. E. Class February 11-14. All packets and donations will be due on Friday, February 15. Your child should have brought home their packets on Friday. If you need another packet, just let me know. We have plenty. You can download the Kids Heart Challenge free of charge to get started with online donations at heart.org/KidsHeartChallenge. If you have any questions, please let Coach Hines know. Each student in each grade level that raises the most donations for their grade will receive their own water bottle and whistle and will get to be the P.E. Teacher for a day for their grade. Thank you so much for helping the American Heart Association!

post_text:
Quick Tips from MACS!
Togetherness: Doing things together.
These include singing, listening to the rain. Flying kites. Making mud pies. Making dandelion crowns. Drawing pictures on the sidewalk with chalk. Having a tea party. Taking walks or riding bikes. Playing games. Going to the movies. Reading. Simply being together!

Holding family meetings: Meetings bring the family together. Kindergarten-age children are capable of being part of a short and simple meeting. Starting early will establish the family meeting as a tradition. Plan meetings to discuss and write down family rules and the consequences of disobeying them. Hold meetings to discuss good things too. Meetings can be held to celebrate a school or family success or to decide how to reinforce and increase progress.

post_text:
More Quick Tips from MACS!
Building Good Character Continued.

Self discipline
-Clean up after yourself. If you leave a mess, so will your children.
-Don't spend what you can't afford. Your children will learn to budget.
-Cooperate with others. Your children will learn teamwork.
-Research your decisions. Your children will learn to make good choices.
-Demonstrate negotiation skills. Your children will learn to negotiate.
-Reward responsible decisions with words of praise.

Individuality
-Teach your children to stand up for their beliefs and values.
-Support their individual interests, even if they differ from yours.
-Don't have a "plan" for what you want your children to be.
-Don't make comparisons of your children to others.
-Let your children make decisions whenever it is safe to do so.

post_text:
Quick Tips from MACS! Building Good Character in Children.
Good character traits are developed through the examples you set, as well as by direct teaching. Here are some suggestion to help your children learn responsibility, self-discipline, individuality, respect, courtesy, and compassion.

Responsibility:
-Keep promises!
-Give children chores at home.
-When conflicts happen, deal directly with your child.
-When you make a mistake, admit it and take care of it.
-Demonstrate initiative and reward it in your children.
-Cause leads to effect. Discuss the consequences of actions.
-Offer your children choices.
-Respect your children's needs and wants. But remember, you make the final decision.

Check back tomorrow for more ways to build good character!

post_text:
Quick tips from MACS!
Ways to promote good attendance:
-Try not to to schedule medical appointments during school hours. Enjoy vacations as a family when school is out on break, not when school is in session.
- Don't let your child stay home unless he/she is truly sick. Headaches and stomachaches may be a sign of stress. Talk to your child if this is a problem.
- Help your child maintain routines, such as waking up on time every morning, going to school, doing homework when he/she gets home and getting to bed early enough to get plenty of sleep.

Talk about school:
-Take time every day to discuss your child's day at school, and have him/her share a favorite moment or event that occurred or what was learned that day.

post_text:
Quick Tips From MACS!

Good attendance makes a difference. Research has shown that good school attendance is one of the biggest factors influencing a child's academic success. As a parent or caregiver, you play an important role in your child's education, and making sure your child is in school on time, every day, is essential!
